1 It has been before observed, that the terme of a logical proposition are the noun ond the verb; the former as subject, the latter as predicate. In propositione tertii adjacentis, the copula and predicate are considered as equivalent toa single verb. When the terms are transposed, the noun 'must become a verb to form the new predicate, and the verb a noun to form the new subject For this reason, all propositions should be resolved into the form tertii adjacentis before conversion; in order that the predicate may be freed from the consignifica- tion of time, so as to form a noun, and the copula may be left to unite with the subject and form a verb.
